comments: This is a big misunderstanding of share price vs market cap. Stocks are like big pies; the share price is equal to how thin they cut the slices. author: @raymondwong2521
comments: I was in Tesla, NIO, xpeng, Nikola.  I bought Tesla at $55 (or $11 split-adjusted) sold at $6,000 (or $1,200 split-adjusted).  I bought NIO at $4-$16, sold off at $48ish, I bought Xpeng at $17, sold off at $55-65, I bought Nikola at $12-18, sold off at $75-92.  Note that my selling prices never were among the highest points of stock prices of these companies, nor have I ever been able to buy these shares at the lowest price points possible.  However, i have made tons of green with my strategy.  You have to monitor the market sentiment.  If you fail to monitor what the markets are likely to do in the next 12 months, you are doomed.  For now, the next 12 months is more a wash to me.  Not a definite up nor down trend.  I only feel there will likely be lots of ups and downs i.e. volatility.  However, Federal Reserve Bank's meeting on March 14-15 will give us some clarity.  If they decide to not increase rates  at as fast as the speed they have previously mentioned, stocks could go crazy up in the short term.  By the way, I have been shorting Rivian since $103 a share.  I am still having my short position with Rivian.  That is a company that is only worth no more than $5 billion market cap and I think I am already quite generous to give Rivian a 5 billion usd market cap even when it is failing with its production ramp.   Back to NIO, I think NIO will have some chances of hitting $10.  Will it go below?  That will largely depend on how SEC will frame its mentality towards delisting the rest of ADRs companies in the US, other than the five companies it has already identified.  Also, if NIO will let US auditors review its financials, who know it could happen either sooner or later, then a huge turnaround will likely be coming.  If you have the crystal balls, you are more than welcome to let me know.  Meanwhile, all EV companies are going through the 2000-2001 period of the dot coms for now.  Look at Mullen Automotive, almost under half a dollar just two weeks ago.  It is a great time to short stocks.  Even DocuSign with its huge market share is seeing its unbeatable downtrend.  When will be the bottom?  When it is too attractive as far as valuation is concerned and that holding other assets seems stupid compared to coming back to these assets on fire sale.  However, we have not reached that point yet.  When NIO will be $10, that just might happen, but yes, $5 will surely be much better.  I am patient :)

Would it be wise for someone getting started with very little money to invest $100 into Ethereum just to get the ball rolling? Or would the returns be too little and be better served in another smaller stock?

author: @TyrantT316
comments:
Here's advice I can give that person based on my mistakes. Think about what you're expecting or hoping for with that $100.

If you're looking to turn $100 into $200, $400, $1000 asap, just note that some of these like Ethereum are longer term plays. They come with volitility so that $100 may quickly become $96 on a dip. It's a game of patience or else you'll be selling at losses to invest your remainder on plays already peaking. If you're just trying to get something started but want to truly have a chance at building wealth, research and keep investing more when you can into diverse portfolio.

@Everything Money¬† ive been studying this company a lot and 40% for 10 years is way too high, insanely high, I would even doubt 20%.
Their deliveries last year seem to wildly change based on the months where chinese consumers had more or less demand for cars. For example December where chinese consumers had expiring benefits buying EVs.
If they had high demand their deliveries should be more stable those months, as they would be delivered as they were produced, sugests to me they are not production constrained but are already at this low numbers demand constrained.
Also the constant launch of new models is another evidence they are having problems with demand, why would you launch new models every 6 months increasing more and more complexity if cant produce enough to satisfy demand on the current models. author: @paulwilson1500
comments: Paul, I'm just not convinced that NIO's battery swap approach to recharging will fly outside of China.  Now maybe this is perfectly fine for the Chinese market, but I don't see it taking hold in Europe or the U.S. so I'm not sure how much growth they will have beyond the Chinese market.

author: @akm824
comments: Why wont work outside of China?

author: @EverythingMoney
comments: And thats ok , i personally have Baba , and dont want more Chinese exposure, at least for now .AP

author: @oppionatedindividual8256
comments: Firstly, China is a massive market anyways, secondly, I think some people might be open to it and it could become the new fad to battery swap instead of conventional charging

author: @paulwilson1500
comments:
@@akm824 There are several reasons why.  First is that none of the other major EV manufacturers (Tesla, VW, Nissan, BYD) have adopted it.  In order to make swapping work, you need coverage of swapping stations so that you can be assured that you can "refill" when you go any distance.  Right now all the emphasis is on building out charging stations.  Don't forget that a large percentage of people who have bought EVs can charge from their own homes.  Only a small percentage of charging is done at public stations.  With swapping, you absolutely have to have a network of swap stations to make it work.

The other reason I don't think it will work is psychological and cultural.  In the U.S. - and maybe to a lesser extent in Europe - we have a general philosophy of "buy-to-own" when it comes to cars rather than "buy-to-rent".  Could that change?  Maybe, but I think there would be a kind of built-in resistance to being beholden to someone else to make driving feasible that could only be overcome by knowing there is a reliable network of swap stations.  It's just too easy to plug in at home.

comments:
Tesla deliveries Q4 2021: 308,000
NIO Q4 2021 deliveries: 25,034
NIO @ 8.1% of Tesla deliveries

Tesla Q3 2021 Revenue: 13.76B
NIO Q3 2021 Revenue: 1.3B
NIO @ 9.4% of Tesla

Tesla market cap 822B
NIO market cap 25.56B
NIO @ 2.62% of Tesla

Tesla delivery growth for year 2021: 87%
NIO delivery growth for year 2021: 109%
NIO @ 22.44% more delivery growth than Tesla

If NIO was currently as profitable and valued like Tesla, based on current delivery numbers/revenue, NIOs market cap would be 69.87B, and the share price would be $44.93

Given the projected 100% growth and profitability heading into 2023, $80 would be a realistic price target provided the numbers can be met and profitability is achieved.

Risks:
-Delisting, a loss of 80% of trading volume
-Worldwide recession - decreased demand for premium EVs
-Growth stagnation due to increased competition
-Chip shortage
-Battery shortage

Advantages:
-William Li
-Backed by the CCP
-Possible partnership with BYD
-ET5, direct competition for the Model 3
-Lidar, self driving as a service, subscription fees.
-China
-Oil prices
-Global expansion
-Battery swap & Battery as a service, rental fees.
-No fear of battery degradation, resale value
-NIO's control of the 2nd hand market
-Customer service and brand recognition.

Remember, Amazon's share price dropped over 90% during the dot-com bubble even though it continued to grow. Anything is possible in the short term.

You guys need to do more research into EVs before you start talking about manufacturing, net profits, production volumes etc... you don't understand the market & compeititon for the businesses you are valuing, you don't know who manufactures and who doesn't or how powerful the backing of the CCP is. You cannot make direct comparison with Ford and GM, not because Teslas is/isn't a car company, or Fisker, Rivian, Lucid, Nio etc... but if nothing else because their factories are built from the ground up as EV production facilities... not a 50 year old converted ICE factory. Ford and GM and ALL the legacy manufacturers have a LONG way to go to catch up to build the priduction, and that's before they get good as software, FSD, battery technology, weight reduciton/efficiency, etc. The only legacy car companies that stand a chance are Hyundai/Kia and VW Group, a sonly they have dedicated EV R&D and priduction in scale now.

The whole point of these high growth speculative stocks is people want to get in a bottom (the beginning of the storey), because the winners will be huge. author: @johannbrauer9285
comments:
Highly unscientific analysis from China: I live in an "expensive" suburb of Chongqing. In our underground garage, one can spot a few Bentleys, lots of Porsches a Pink Maserati, and a Pink Porsche 911 (both driven by teenage girls). The rest are mostly German cars. One very sad exception is our 10-year-old Honda CRV :) which is by far the shyttiest car in the garage.

What I am beginning to see more are NIOs, XPengs, and Li Autos plus the occasional BYD Hans.
Li One is an oddity. Earlier the only other options were Toyota LandCruiser or Buick GL8. Li one is cheaper, PHEV, and looks much better.
XPengs are usually progressive families' second cars. One of my students' dad has a P7, but the girl likes his dad's Range Rover better.

A clear exception is NIO. It is considered to be of better quality and has a higher status than its German counterparts.
This reputation is pure gold for NIO. The Chinese are very brand aware when it comes to cars (and everything else). In their minds, NIO ranks higher than the German brands. NIO's design isn't that flashy, but one can spot a NIO half a mile away. It has that elegance that makes it pop up.
I have had several rides in an ES6 and the car is pure luxury. If one didn't know what car they are sitting in, they would guess a German car twice the prICE ( :) )


Geelys and BYDs one meets here more often as DiDi (Chinese Uber) cars. DiDi drivers work for their money and they use the most cost-effective vehicle for their purposes. I use one several times a week and the ride is as good as any European ICE taxi. WE also have another service, "CaoCao" that only uses electric cars. I would prefer them, but their phone app is only in Chinese. DiDi app is in English as well.

NIO is a very expensive car here and will be even more expensive in the west. We're talking about a close to $100k price tag for the top models in the west.
My friend's NIO ES6 is two years old now and it looks and feels new. It is clearly an expensive luxury car, not a bargain bin Chinese copy of anything.

author: @johannbrauer9285
comments: A (possibly) interesting addition to my story: The underground garage parking spot costs between $20k and $30k, so you wouldn't be parking a Yugo there :) My wife bought the parking spot with the condo when the Honda was new and not quite so embarrassing to own.

author: @haleis4117
comments:
Remember that NIO actually produces no cars themselves and owns no factories. Their cars are produced for them by a state owned car manufacturer, JAC. So they are very much less in control of their profit margin than Xpeng and Li  Auto and almost the opposite of BYD which, as you very well know, produce not just their own cars but their own batteries and chips.
I have owned each of the above companies, though in much smaller amounts than Tesla but several months ago profitably sold my NIO to buy more BYD.
Finally, Li Auto does not produce a plug-in hybrid as you like to describe them, they produce a BEV with 200+ miles of range with a small motor and gas storage to provide extended range (and no range anxiety) and that is very different than a typical plug-in and will introduce two new BEV models in 2023.

author: @haleis4117
comments: @@joeking433 PHEV owns factories and produces their own cars. In fact they are the only car manufacturer who literally accepted Elon's invitation to use Tesla's intellectual property and has produced the most Tesla-like cars. They have also, btw, been accused of hiring an ex-Tesla employee who stole extensive software from Tesla. I do believe that not owning your own factories or producing your own cars vs. designing them and having someone else produce them presents a an incremental financial burden and a possible future conflict of interest.

author: @deragoth4250
comments:
Battery swapping is a cool idea but I am not sure it will solve the holiday surge problem especially if everyone buys a Nio. After a number of swaps the supply of fully charged batteries will be exhausted. During normal daily operation there will be time to charge them for next customer but during the holidays where everyone is travelling this will be more difficult. Nio will not be able to supply more batteries or swapping stations just to accommodate the holiday surge because it will be uneconomical. 2 things that currently helps Nio customers - Nio is quite expensive and less common so battery swapping is still ok as demand is not that great. Also I guess so Nio owners can swap for the bigger battery pack so they may make the trip to their hometown in one go.

Anyway who knows. Maybe in 10 years time, all EVs (even the cheap ones) will have the tech to charge the cars as quickly as if we were in a petrol station and there will be EV power stations every 20km or so on the highway.

author: @guycocoa211
comments: I am a NIO shareholder, and a fan of battery swapping, but at peak times battery swapping is not a solution. Assuming 5 minutes per swap, then only 12 swaps can be done per hour. A set of 12 chargers could provide the same throughput. The problem with charging during peak times is that it becomes a hoarding situation. Because charging is viewed as being in short supply, people hoard it by charging their cars to 100%.  Charging from 80%-100% can take longer than 0%-80%. What the charging stations should do during peak times to increase throughput, and eliminate the hoarding mentality, is double the price per KWh when charging above 80% and quadruple it when charging above 90%. People would realize that their hoarding is going to cost them a lot, so they would leave and that would make the most efficient use of the chargers.

author: @HeliTom84
comments:
Will be interesting to see how it plays out. I‚Äôm a bit skeptical about the whole BaaS deal. Is swapping so much better? I will use Tesla as example in this. 
Let‚Äôs break it down;

1) if Nio is going to be mass volume car, I don‚Äôt think Nio will have enough swap stations for the customer to really have a ~4 minute swap. They will most likely experience queues, and then a 20 min supercharge with Tesla once a week / >500km road trips doesn‚Äôt matter at all. Also; most people charge at their home / work here. 

2) each swap stations will be extremely costly. There‚Äôs hard to even make enough batteries today for each car, none the less for 14x1000x swap stations. Also, each swap station needs about 5 or 6 full time operators, and here in Norway that‚Äôs going to cost a easy $100k a year for each employee that works there. That‚Äôs $600k in just salaries, pension and other company taxes for one swap station. 

3) BaaS prices are high per kw compared to a Tesla supercharge price. You‚Äôre looking at double the price here in Norway.

4) Nio Norway is claiming it needs 15000km / every service to maintain warranty. If this is true, that‚Äôs really bad IMO. Tesla don‚Äôt have any service intervals that you have to bring it in for to maintain warranty. 

5) batteries are proven to be long lasting with little degradation and safe and reliable. However If a Tesla needs a new battery, they will change it under 8 year warranty. It‚Äôs no hassle for the customer really. You get Tesla lender car meanwhile they do the service in a couple of days or so. 

6) Nio charging speed is slow. Tesla is way faster and it keeps getting faster and faster by the years. Supercharging infrastructure is great here and I‚Äôve never experienced that I have to wait in line to charge. And this is Tesla-land where it‚Äôs the no1 most selling car in the country. 
It‚Äôs also very quick to set up more superchargers and Tesla will have solar powered supercharger stations in combination with mega packs in the near future.

7) Tesla have done swapping in 90 seconds in the past. Why did they stop doing it ? It‚Äôs obvious. 

Here‚Äôs a few points also ; https://youtu.be/YyLU_jT-2v8

author: @jb9652
comments:
I agree that the TA looks frightening - and always did because unlike Tesla the baseline (long period mean) wasn't inclined upward, indicating that there was no overall money inflow. I think the $18 support might hold. If not, the $12 one. üôÇ

(Incidentally, my big $12 NIO position stopped out, just like my big $18 LCID position (literally by $0.02). My two biggest (totally huge) mistakes in the past year).

Alternatively, I'm thinking that NIO's current meandering around $30 might establish a new support. After all, the company was quite a different beast at the time of the old supports. It has its own factory in the pipeline now.

If the share price does halve, I reckon it could happen as part of (precursor to) major bubble deflation, including deflation of the delirious mega caps e.g. AAPL.

The NIO chart looks the same to me as AMC, suggesting that the value of the company is currently irrelevant. My hope is that the value of NIO is in fact relevant, and the chart will eventually morph into an appropriate one for the stock.

I‚Äôd by the ET5 if it were available in the US and priced competitively, but NIO has been pretty quiet on how much volume they intend to have in the future, and have sounded as though they aim to do BMW-like numbers (2.5m vehicles/year) long-term. Now maybe if NIO actually does sub brands (which I don‚Äôt necessarily agree with as it‚Äôs a legacy automaker approach) with more affordable price tags, then they could possibly compete to be the largest. But they haven‚Äôt revealed anything related to a single sub brand yet. comments: This seems to mean that investors owning the U.S. listed shares would be holding the same security that is listed on Singapore's exchange, and would be able to trade it. Under the Holding Foreign Companies Accountable Act (HFCAA), the SEC can delist foreign companies that fail to meet U.S. accounting and audit standards for three straight years. Nio is already listed in both the U.S. and Hong Kong, and said it plans to work to maintain its presence on both exchanges. But the proposal to list on a third exchange looks to be a backup plan in case Nio is ultimately unable to comply with U.S. laws and regulations. U.S. investors are taking that as good news, which helped the stock to stage a bit of a recovery Friday.

author: @Analytical_Visionary
comments: That is a NIO 1.0 swap station where the user has to step out and a NIO engineer drives it into the swap station. Also in 1.0 swap station the vehicle is lifted during a battery swap. The NIO 2.0 swap stations allow the user to stay in the vehicle and also the vehicle automatically reverses into the swap station. During the battery swap the vehicle is not lifted and the swap itself is under 5 mins. 2.0 stations also hold more batteries than compared to 1.0. In Europe NIO is rolling out the 2.0 battery swaps.

author: @peterklausner9727
comments: Great content on CSRC announcement ‚úÖ. Delisting IMO through the HFCAA or the AHFCAA from the US side didn't seem to be a realistic threat to NIO. Many reported that this as a tool to delist all Chinese companies. Not the case, was a tool to get further accounting oversight out of China to detect & delist fraudulent Chinese companies.. Many of the workings are still being sorted out.. But first a company needs to be identified.. & now from the Chinese side the CSRC has stated that they support VIE'S, where before they were technically illegal!!! Now the CSRC also will allow foreign regulators access to accounting compliance for VIE listed companies!! Some sectors that are telecoms, or companies that are 100% state owned (banks), or other companies that are forbidden due to security reasons obviously won't be included in any VIE structured company listing.. But for the EV sector.. This isn't a sector at risk & is actually a priority for the CCP.. Things very evident like curbing pollution, Tesla being allowed to build a factory in China & have no Chinese 50/50 partner, (a first).. Also the CSRC recently have announced 100% foreign ownership in the NEV sector.. Now this big announcement by June or before... Great news, because I have a few shares of NIO..

author: @busterboyd4125
comments: All these stocks are losers. We're in a recession so hold your cash and when the time is right dollar cost average into Large Cap Growth and Value. If you still want SOFI and PLTR wait until they hit low single digits. PLTR at $3 seems more palatable. Although PLTR feels like a dilution scam to me. Where insiders are the only ones that make real money until they dilute the company out of business.

author: @ytfinance
comments: Do you think none of these stocks are going to rebound in the future? If so why?

author: @busterboyd4125
comments:
@@ytfinance Depends on your time frame. Do I think these stocks will rebound during a bear market? Absolutely not. Do I think 10 years down the road could some see gains? Possibly. 

I have zero confidence in NIO. They are only still in existence because the ccp bailed them out a few times. 

I'm not super confident in SOFI because there is so much competition in this space. 

PLTR has the best outlook of the bunch but the company shows no respect for fiduciary duty. So far they only care about lining their own pockets. A diluted stock is a worthless stock. It doesn't matter how many billions a company makes if they spend it all on their staff. That is a system created to serve themselves and not the stockholder. So until this changes a big fat NO to PLTR. I once held a large position on PLTR until I realized it was a scam and fortunately I was able to unload all of my holdings at a small profit. I would look at several key things to change before investing in them again. They have to reduce employee stock options way down, they need several quarters of stock buybacks, and they have to show consistent sales and  profit growth.

author: @niruanya
comments: Great video, as always! What people like Cathie Wood (who called Nio ‚Äúa battery company, not an EV company‚Äù) fail to realize is Nio is poised for TOTAL autonomy. You can‚Äôt automate a Tesla Supercharger. You can‚Äôt automate a gas pump (or, at least, the awkward mechanics of such would preclude efficiency and scalability). This is IDEAL for fleet vehicles and commuters. You don‚Äôt have to build 800V infrastructures, degrade batteries quicker with high voltage charging and, consequentially, produce more waste. You don‚Äôt have to wait upwards of 30 minutes to get a full charge (queued behind others who also have to wait at least that long). And say there‚Äôs a power outage in certain towns/regions, a Nio Power Swap Station housing 10+ charged batteries could provide much needed power to essential services in the vicinity. If EVs are ‚Äúthe thing‚Äù, Nio‚Äôs approach makes the most sense.

author: @PLO007
comments:
I beg to differ on NIO's case in particular. 

The one thing that distinguishes NIO apart from all the other China brands, whether it be China fashion or electronics brands, is NIO's attention-to-details. NIO's sense of attention-to-the-details is unheard for a China brand. 

The attention-to-details, the artistry and the creativity, is what sets the Armanis et al. apart in the Euro luxury brand sphere. NIO seems to "get" that. And they are trying to implement those detailed qualities into their hardware/software, and services (especially services). As long as NIO keeps to their attention-to-details craftsmanship, they will not become the often mocked 'China brand' image the outside world associate all China brands with. They have a shot at the luxury prestige image if they keep focusing on the quality of their details in everything they do.

author: @austinlittke7688
comments:
I'd take some when it becomes obvious that perhaps you should. At worst, the stock doesn't pull back significantly and offer you a chance to buy back the shares you sold but you can find another stock underperforming to buy stock in instead, at best, you can double, triple etc the amount of shares you had or secure profit to keep cash on the side. For reference, I remember when nio shot up over 100% at first and my plan was to sell most my shares and put it into tesla which at the time hadn't shot up...didn't end up doing it, but tesla ended up shooting up 100% and Nio did nothing but drop. 

Another instance, i saw my overall portfolio just shoot up a ridiculous amount that looked unnatural, and i knew i should secure all profits and sell everything and just wait for the market to correct, well, needless to say I didn't and the market crashed since then and I lost $100,000.

I was too dogmatic with "ok, im gonna stick to a buy and hold strategy". Don't be like that. I'd start securing profits on some stocks and wait for a pullback after this huge run, i'll be doing that.
